{"title_page": "Jake Arrieta", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Jake Arrieta\n| image         = Jake Arrieta (47501185272) (cropped).jpg\n| caption       = Arrieta with the Phillies in 2019\n| team          = Philadelphia Phillies\n| number        = 49\n| position      = [[Pitcher]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1986|3|6}}\n| birth_place   = [[Farmington, Missouri|Farmington]], [[Missouri]]\n| bats          = Right\n| throws        = Right\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = June 10\n| debutyear     = 2010\n| debutteam     = Baltimore Orioles\n| statyear      = 2019 season\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n| stat1value    = 106\u201375\n| stat2label    = [[Earned run average]]\n| stat2value    = 3.72\n| stat3label    = [[Strikeout]]s\n| stat3value    = 1,318\n| teams         =\n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2013}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n| awards        =\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2016 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2016]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2016}})\n* [[Cy Young Award|NL Cy Young Award]] (2015)\n* [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2016)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual wins leaders|MLB wins leader]] (2015)\n* Pitched two [[no-hitter]]s (2015, 2016)\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Baseball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Baseball at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[World University Baseball Championship|2006 Havana]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Jacob Joseph Arrieta''' (born March 6, 1986) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[Chicago Cubs]]. \n\nArrieta played college baseball at [[Weatherford College|Weatherford Junior College]] and at [[Texas Christian University]] (TCU). He was an All-American and was named Mountain West Conference Pitcher of the Year at TCU. The Orioles selected Arrieta in the fifth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft|2007 MLB draft]], and he signed a then record contract for a fifth round draft pick. He pitched for the [[United States national baseball team]] at the [[Baseball at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Olympics]], winning the [[bronze medal]]. \n\nHe made his big league debut for the Orioles in 2010, and after four seasons Arrieta was traded to the Cubs in 2013. In 2015, Arrieta led MLB in wins with 22, pitched a [[no-hitter]], and won the 2015 National League [[Cy Young Award]]. In 2016, he was an NL [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All Star]], threw his second no-hitter, was awarded a [[Silver Slugger Award]], and won a [[2016 World Series|World Series]] with the Cubs. \n\nPrior to the start of the 2018 season, Arrieta signed a three-year, $75 million contract as a free agent with the Phillies. In August 2019 it was announced that he would have season-ending surgery to remove a [[bone spur]] in his pitching elbow.\n\n== Amateur career ==\n\nArrieta was born in [[Farmington, Missouri]], to Lou and Lynda Arrieta.<ref name=\"STLtoday\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stltoday.com/sports/columns/benjamin-hochman/hochman-cubs-fan-just-can-t-help-it-even-in/article_cd225980-5c45-5331-9c22-80e3b2510bf5.html | title=Cubs fan just can't help it, even in Cardinals territory | publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch | date=September 23, 2016 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Hochman, Benjamin}}</ref> They moved to Texas four months after Arrieta was born, and he grew up in [[Plano, Texas]], where he attended [[Plano East Senior High School]].<ref name=\"STLtoday\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/community/weatherford-star-telegram/wt-sports/article46195340.html|title=Former Weatherford Coyote wins Cy Young Award|website=star-telegram}}</ref> He was 6\u20131 with a 1.61 ERA as a junior, and 5\u20134 with a 1.30 ERA as a senior.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://gofrogs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=331|title=Jake Arrieta - Baseball|website=TCU Athletics}}</ref> As a high school senior he was selected by the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in the 31st round of the [[2004 Major League Baseball draft|2004 draft]], but instead he chose to attend college.<ref name=\"TCU Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gofrogs.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/arrieta_jake00.html |title=Jake Arrieta |publisher=TCU Athletics |access-date=August 31, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809040439/http://www.gofrogs.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/arrieta_jake00.html |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1818294#rd31 |title=MLB 2004 Draft selections, Day 2 |publisher=ESPN |date=June 8, 2004 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nArrieta attended [[Weatherford College|Weatherford Junior College]] for his freshman year in 2005, posting a 6\u20132 [[win\u2013loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] with a 3.43 ERA.<ref name=\"TCU Bio\" /> Following his freshman year, Arrieta was selected by the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] in the 26th round of the [[2005 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nInstead, he opted to transfer to [[Texas Christian University]] (TCU), where he played for the [[TCU Horned Frogs baseball|TCU Horned Frogs baseball team]] for his sophomore and junior seasons, and studied [[sport psychology]].<ref name=\"TCU Bio\" /><ref name=\"sport psych\" /> During the summer of 2005, prior to enrolling at TCU, Arrieta participated in summer collegiate baseball with the McKinney Marshalls of the [[Texas Collegiate League]], and posted a 4\u20133 record in 10 starts with a 1.87 ERA over {{frac|62|2|3}} [[inning]]s pitched.<ref name=\"TCU Bio\" /> During his sophomore year in 2006, Arrieta led [[college baseball]] with 14 wins and had a 2.35 ERA over 19 appearances, and he had 111 [[strikeout]]s in 111 innings.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref name=\"sport psych\">{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/110014572/strong-body-and-mind-fuel-cubs-jake-arrieta |publisher=MLB.com |title=Strong body and mind fuel Cubs' Arrieta |author=Muskat, Carrie |date=February 22, 2015 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> He won the [[Mountain West Conference]] Pitcher of the Year Award and was named a [[College Baseball All-America Team|Second-Team College Baseball All-American]] after his sophomore year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gofrogs.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/111506aaa.html |title=Arrieta named NCBWA preseason 1st-team All-American |publisher=TCU Athletics |date=November 15, 2006 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nin his junior year in 2007, he was 9\u20133 with a 3.01 ERA.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He was named First-team All-Mountain West in 2007.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nArrieta first joined the [[United States national baseball team]] in 2006, and helped the team win the [[World University Baseball Championship]] in [[Cuba]]. He was 4\u20130 with 34 strikeouts and a 0.27 ERA\u2014allowing just one [[earned run]] in 35 innings pitched over six starts for the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gofrogs.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/arrieta_jake00.html |title=TCU Athletics |accessdate=August 18, 2008}}</ref> In his first start at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing, Arrieta pitched six innings and struck out seven in Team USA's 9\u20131 victory over the [[China national baseball team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080818&content_id=3328463&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=More tension than expected in U.S. win |accessdate=August 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\n\n=== Draft and minors ===\n[[File:Jake Arrieta on August 8, 2009, Futures at Fenway.jpg|200px|thumb|Arrieta pitching for the [[Norfolk Tides]] in 2009]]\nThe [[Baltimore Orioles]] selected Arrieta in the fifth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]]. He signed with the Orioles for a $1.1&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]], which at the time was the largest signing bonus for a fifth round draft pick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/stats/stats.jsp?n=Jake%20Arrieta&pos=P&sid=milb&t=p_pbp&pid=453562 |title=Minor League Baseball |accessdate=August 18, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://starlocalmedia.com/planocourier/sports/arrieta-to-live-olympic-dream/article_68bbfcbb-f569-5cdc-bed9-d07350b93086.html |title=Arrieta To Live Olympic Dream |work=Plano Star Courier |date=August 7, 2008 |accessdate=August 31, 2015 |author=O'Brien, Ben}}</ref><ref name=\"WT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/blog/national-pastime/2008/jun/5/prospect-qa---jake-arrieta-baltimore-orioles/ |work=Washington Times |title=Prospect Q ;amp& A: Jake Arrieta, Orioles |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=LeBlanc, Jay}}</ref>\n\nArrieta made his professional debut in the [[Arizona Fall League]] with the [[Phoenix Desert Dogs]] in 2007. He posted 16 scoreless innings, while striking out 16 over 14 appearances, and helped lead the Desert Dogs to the Arizona League championship.<ref name=\"WT\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://napavalleyregister.com/sports/another-banner-year-for-desert-dogs/article_aa6db25e-e40e-586e-9c58-634181ccff63.html |title=Another banner year for Desert Dogs |date=November 24, 2007 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |publisher=Napa Valley Register |author=Miller, Harrell}}</ref>\n\nArrieta pitched to a 6\u20135 record with a 2.87 ERA and 120 strikeouts over 113 innings for the [[Frederick Keys]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Carolina League]] when his season ended in order to allow him to play for the [[United States at the 2008 Summer Olympics|USA Baseball team]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baseball.realgm.com/analysis/569/Prospect-Report-Jake-Arrieta-Baltimore-Orioles |title=Prospect Report: Jake Arrieta, Baltimore Orioles |publisher=RealGM |author=Reina, Christopher |date=March 9, 2009 |accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.njcaa.org/sports/bsb/2007-08/releases/2008-07-25_6797.html |publisher=NJCAA |date=July 25, 2008 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |title=Two Former NJCAA Baseball Players Named to USA Olympic Team}}</ref>\n\n===Baltimore Orioles (2010\u20132013)===\n[[File:Jake Arrieta 2011.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Arrieta pitching for the Orioles in 2011]]\nArrieta made his major league debut on June 10, 2010, against the [[New York Yankees]] at [[Oriole Park at Camden Yards|Camden Yards]]. He pitched six innings, giving up four hits and three runs, [[strikeout|striking out]] six and earning the win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100610&content_id=11036810&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=bal |title=O's Arrieta beats Yankees in MLB debut |work=Baltimore Orioles |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> For the 2010 season, he was 6\u20136 with a 4.66 ERA in {{frac|100|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/arrieja01.shtml|title=Jake Arrieta Stats|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nHe won the home opener for the Orioles in 2011, and was the youngest opening day starting pitcher for the Orioles since [[Mike Mussina]] in 1994.<ref name=\"CT\">{{cite web | url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/ct-jake-arrieta-cubs-giants-haugh-spt-0810-20150809-column.html | title=Cubs are for real, and so is Jake Arrieta, the ace of their pitching staff | publisher=Chicago Tribune | date=August 5, 2019 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Haugh, David}}</ref> In 2011, he was 10\u20138 with a 5.05 ERA in {{frac|113|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Arrieta was again named the opening day starter for the Orioles in 2012. After starting the 2012 season 3\u20139 with an ERA of 6.13, Arrieta was demoted to Triple-A on July 6, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/team/transactions.jsp?c_id=bal#month=7&year=2012&team_id=110%7ctitle=MLB.com |title=Transactions |work=Baltimore Orioles |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nArrieta began the 2013 season with four starts for the Orioles posting a 1\u20131 record and a 6.63 ERA until being sent down to the Triple-A [[Norfolk Tides]] on April 22 after the Orioles recalled [[Alex Burnett]].<ref name=\"USATODAY2013\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/orioles/2013/06/14/orioles-recall-jake-arrieta-option-kevin-gausman/2425113/ |work=USA Today |title=Orioles option rookie Gausman, recall Arrieta |date=June 14, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlbdailydish.com/2013/4/22/4253904/orioles-demote-jake-arrieta-recall-alex-burnett |publisher=SB Nation |title=Orioles demote Jake Arrieta to Triple-A, recall Alex Burnett |date=April 22, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=Aderhold, Nathan}}</ref> He was recalled by the Orioles on May 18 and later optioned back down to Triple-A to make room for [[Kevin Gausman]] on May 23.<ref name=\"USATODAY2013\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-05-24/sports/bs-sp-orioles-notes-0524-20130523_1_jake-arrieta-triple-a-norfolk-kevin-gausman |title=Jake Arrieta sent back to Triple-A to make room for Gausman |work=Baltimore Sun |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=Encina, Eduardo}}</ref> He was recalled again on June 14 and Gausman was optioned to Triple-A to make room on the roster for Arrieta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-06-14/sports/bal-pregame-orioles-notes-gausman-arrieta-hammel-reimold-draft-picks-20130614_1_kevin-gausman-triple-a-norfolk-orioles-notes |title=Orioles notes: Gausman not guaranteed to return to majors soon |work=Baltimore Sun |date=June 14, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=Connolly, Dan}}</ref> In 2013 with Baltimore, he was 1\u20132 with a 7.23 ERA in {{frac|23|2|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Through four years with the Orioles, Arrieta posted a record of 20\u201325 and a 5.46 ERA in 358 innings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/02/orioles-trade-cubs-dodgers-marmol_n_3537086.html |publisher=Huffington Post |date=July 2, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |title=Orioles Trade Jake Arrieta, Pedro Strop To Cubs, Who Shipped Carlos Marmol To Dodgers |author=Gonzalez, Anthony}}</ref>\n\n=== Chicago Cubs (2013\u20132017) ===\n\n==== 2013 ====\nOn July 2, 2013, the Orioles traded Arrieta along with [[Pedro Strop]] to the [[Chicago Cubs]] for [[Scott Feldman]] and [[Steve Clevenger]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Drew |title=Orioles Trade Jake Arrieta and Pedro Strop to Cubs for Scott Feldman |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1691801-orioles-trade-jake-arrieta-and-pedro-stropm-to-cubs-for-scott-feldman |website=bleacherreport.com |publisher=bleacher report |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>  He was optioned to the [[Iowa Cubs]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[Pacific Coast League]] upon being acquired. After making 5 starts for Iowa, Arrieta was recalled to start Game 2 of a doubleheader against the Brewers on July 30. In his Chicago debut, he gave up 1 run in 6 innings, earning a no-decision in the 3\u20132 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_07_30_milmlb_chnmlb_2&mode=recap_home&c_id=chc |title=Cubs falter after Arrieta's strong debut |work=MLB.com |first=Manny |last=Randhawa |date=July 31, 2013}}</ref> After the game, Arrieta was optioned to Iowa where he made two more starts before being recalled on August 14 to replace [[Carlos Villanueva (baseball)|Carlos Villanueva]] in the rotation. He made eight more starts before the end of the season. In his nine starts with Chicago, he went 4\u20132 with a 3.66 ERA, striking out 37 in {{frac|51|2|3}} innings. In 30 games (29 starts) in 2013 including the minors, Arrieta went 12\u20139 with a 4.42 ERA, striking out 137 in {{frac|154|2|3}} innings.\n\n==== 2014 ====\nArrieta took no-hitters into the seventh or eighth innings three times in the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Phil |title=Arrieta looks like pitching cornerstone for Cubs |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/95183312/phil-rogers-jake-arrieta-looks-like-pitching-cornerstone-for-cubs |publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=September 18, 2014}}</ref> On June 24, Arrieta retired the first 18 Reds in order, but the perfect game was broken up by Cincinnati's [[Billy Hamilton (baseball, born 1990)|Billy Hamilton]]'s leadoff double in the seventh. On June 30, against the Red Sox, Arrieta took a no-hitter into the 8th until [[Stephen Drew]] singled with two outs the inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=340630102 |title=Jake Arrieta takes no-hit bid into 8th as Cubs blank Red Sox |publisher=ESPN |date=August 1, 2014 |accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2014 season, he posted a 10\u20135 record with a 2.53 ERA, and in {{frac|156|2|3}} innings he gave up 114 hits, walked 41, and struck out 167.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He came in 9th in voting for the National League [[Cy Young Award]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==== 2015 ====\nOn July 12, 2015, Arrieta pitched a [[complete game]] victory over the Chicago White Sox at Wrigley Field, his second complete game of the season and the third of his major league career.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muskat |last2=Garno |first1=Carrie |first2=Greg |title=Arrieta goes distance, goes deep in 10th win |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/136293868/jake-arrieta-dominates-white-sox-for-10th-win |work=MLB.com |date=July 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jake Arrieta masterful as Cubs avoid sweep vs. White Sox |url=http://www.csnchicago.com/cubs/jake-arrieta-masterful-cubs-avoid-sweep-vs-white-sox |archive-url=https://archive.today/20151117055959/http://www.csnchicago.com/cubs/jake-arrieta-masterful-cubs-avoid-sweep-vs-white-sox |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 17, 2015 |work=[[Comcast SportsNet Chicago|CSNChicago.com]] |date=July 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 12, 2015 }}</ref> On August 20, Arrieta became the first MLB pitcher to win 15 games in the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowman |last2=Muskat |first1=Mark |first2=Carrie |title=Arrieta first to 15 wins as Cubs rout Braves |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/144338294/jake-arrieta-wins-15th-as-cubs-rout-braves |work=MLB.com |date=August 21, 2015 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Ten days later, Arrieta [[no-hitter|no-hit]] the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] at [[Dodger Stadium]] for the [[List of Chicago Cubs no-hitters|14th no-hitter in Cubs history]]. He struck out 12 batters, including all three batters he faced in both the first and ninth innings. [[Sandy Koufax]] had been the last pitcher to complete a no-hitter by striking out all three batters he faced in the ninth inning, doing so against the Cubs in [[Sandy Koufax's perfect game|his 1965 perfect game]]\u2014a game also played at Dodger Stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/chicago-cubs-los-angeles-dodgers-350830119/ |title=Chi Cubs at LA Dodgers \u2013 2015-08-30 \u2013 Major League Baseball \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |date=August 31, 2015 |work=Yahoo! Sports |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> Arrieta was named the [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|NL Player of the Week]] for August 24\u201330 and [[Major League Baseball Pitcher of the Month Award|NL Pitcher of the Month]] for August with a 6\u20130 and a 0.43 ERA and the no-hitter. The right-hander held opposing hitters to a .130 batting average and a .196 on-base percentage in August and struck out 43 batters while walking just 10.<ref name=AwardLastWeekAugust2015>{{cite web |last=Press release |title=Jake Arrieta of the Chicago Cubs named National League Player of the Week |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146492750 |work=MLB.com |date=September 3, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=AwardAugust2105>{{cite web |last=Fordin |first=Spencer |title=Arrieta named NL Pitcher of the Month: Right-hander goes 6\u20130 with 0.43 ERA in August, capping month with no-hitter |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/147184218 |work=MLB.com |date=September 3, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>  On September 22, Arrieta won his 20th game of the season, throwing a three-hitter against the Brewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/151016074 |title=Arrieta, Bryant make history in Cubs' win |accessdate=September 23, 2015 |last1=Garno |first1=Greg |last2=Jackson |first2=John |date=September 22, 2015 |work=[[MLB]]}}</ref>  With 11 more strikeouts in that 4\u20130 Cubs victory at Wrigley, he was the first MLB pitcher to win 20 games this season and had his fourth complete game and third shutout of the season.\n\nAfter the 2015 All-Star break, he gave up 9 earned runs during 15 starts over {{frac|107|1|3}} innings for a 0.75 ERA, the lowest in MLB history in the second half.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/14165080/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-wins-national-league-cy-young-award |title=NL Cy Young winner Jake Arrieta finally put 'small things in place' |publisher=ESPN |author=Greenberg, Jon |date=November 19, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/eye-on-baseball/25325940/cubs-jake-arrieta-sets-all-time-mark-with-075-era-in-second-half |title=Cubs' Jake Arrieta sets record with 0.75 ERA in second half |publisher=CBS Sports |author=[[Dayn Perry|Perry, Dayn]] |date=October 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref> On October 5, he was again named NL Pitcher of the Month for his 4\u20130 September record with a 0.45 ERA.<ref name=AwardSeptember2015>{{cite web |title=Cubs superhuman ace Jake Arrieta wins consecutive NL Pitcher of the Month |url=http://www.csnchicago.com/cubs/cubs-superhuman-ace-jake-arrieta-wins-consecutive-nl-pitcher-month |website=csnchicago.com |publisher=CSN CHGO |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor the season, Arrieta's 22\u20136 record and 1.77 ERA (second in the NL) made him only the fifth pitcher to win at least 22 games with no more than six losses and a sub-2.00 ERA since the earned run became an official stat in 1913.<ref>Verducci, Tom [https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/03/28/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-profile The Revenant: How Jake Arrieta came back from the baseball dead] ''Sports Illustrated''. March 30, 2016</ref> Arrieta's 2015 season has been widely compared to [[Bob Gibson]]'s 1968 season in which Gibson won the National League MVP and Cy Young Awards after posting a [[live-ball era]] record 1.12 ERA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsworld.nbcsports.com/jake-arrieta-leads-cubs-past-pirates/ |title=CHANNELING BOB GIBSON |publisher=NBC Sports |date=October 8, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |author=[[Joe Posnanski|Posnanski, Joe]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/09/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-mlb |title=Cubs ace Jake Arrieta is 9\u20130 with a 0.48 ERA since the start of August |work=USA Today |author=Berg, Ted |date=September 23, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/997874/jake-arrieta-best-non-bob-gibson-19-game-stretch-era-since-1914 |title=Jake Arrieta has the second-best 19-game ERA since 1914 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |author=Ogden, Rob |date=September 29, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119235657/http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/997874/jake-arrieta-best-non-bob-gibson-19-game-stretch-era-since-1914 |archive-date=November 19, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He led the majors in wins, complete games (4), and [[shutout]]s (3), and led the National League in hits per 9 innings pitched (5.895) and games started (33).<ref name=autogenerated2 />  He also led the majors in lowest [[home runs per nine innings]] (0.39).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2015&month=0&season1=2015&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,a|title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2015 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Dashboard - FanGraphs Baseball|website=www.fangraphs.com}}</ref> His .786 win-loss percentage and his 0.865 [[walk]]s plus hits per innings pitched were second in the NL.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n[[File:Jake Arrieta does pushups.jpg|thumb|Jake Arrieta does pushups before his start in [[2015 National League Championship Series#Game 2|Game 2 of the 2015 NLCS]]]]\nArrieta started the [[2015 National League Wild Card Game]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Muskat |first=Carrie |title=Jake Arrieta to start NL wild card game |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/153200532/jake-arrieta-to-start-nl-wild-card-game |work=MLB.com |date=October 4, 2015 |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> He pitched a complete-game shutout, striking out 11 batters and allowed only four hits to defeat the Pittsburgh Pirates 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chc vs Pit 10/07/2015 Boxscore |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2015_10_07_chnmlb_pitmlb_1#game=2015_10_07_chnmlb_pitmlb_1,game_tab=box,game_state=Wrapup |website=mlb.mlb.com |publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref> He became the first pitcher to post a postseason shutout while striking out at least 10 batters and walking zero.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casella |first1=Paul |title=10 cool facts about Arrieta's Wild Card shutout |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/153648164/10-facts-from-jake-arrieta-in-wild-card-game |website=m.mlb.com |publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref> He is also the first pitcher to have more [[stolen base]]s than runs scored in a postseason game when he stole [[second base]] in the top of the 7th inning. Arrieta was the pitcher of record in the Game 2 loss of the [[2015 National League Championship Series]] to the New York Mets.\n\nArrieta won the [[NL Cy Young Award]] to become the first Cubs pitcher to do so since [[Greg Maddux]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Woo |first1=Jeremy |title=Dallas Keuchel, Jake Arrieta named AL, NL Cy Young Award winners |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/11/18/dallas-keuchel-jake-arrieta-cy-young-award-winners |website=si.com |publisher=Sports Illustratedsi.com |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>  He was the fifth Cubs winner overall, also joining [[Fergie Jenkins]] (1971), [[Bruce Sutter]] (1979) and [[Rick Sutcliffe]] (1984).<ref name=CyYoungESPN /> He also came in sixth in the voting for 2015 NL [[Most Valuable Player Award]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==== 2016 ====\n[[File:Cubs starter Jake Arrieta delivers a pitch in the first inning of World Series Game 6. (30634554251).jpg|thumb|left|Arrieta pitching in Game 6 of the [[2016 World Series]]]]\nOn February 5, 2016, Arrieta and the Cubs agreed on a record [[Salary arbitration|arbitration deal]] worth $10.7 million 2016 salary, the largest one-year contract for a second-time arbitration eligible pitcher, topping [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]]'s $10.1 million salary in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Dayn |title=Cubs Arrieta breaks record with $10.7 million dollar contract |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/eye-on-baseball/25475482/cubs-sign-jake-arrieta-to-107-million-contract-avoid-arbitration |website=cbssports.com |publisher=CBS Sports |accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref>  The club chose him as the [[2016 Chicago Cubs season|2016 season]] Opening Day starting pitcher against the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Angels]] on April 4.<ref name=2016OpeningDay>{{cite web | last = Muskat | first = Carrie | title = Arrieta carries great expectations into Opening Day | url = http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/169885240/cubs-jake-arrieta-ready-for-opening-day-start | work = MLB.com | date = April 1, 2016 | accessdate = April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, Arrieta pitched his second career no-hitter and the [[List of Chicago Cubs no-hitters|15th no-hitter in Cubs history]] against the Cincinnati Reds in a 16\u20130 blowout win.  He walked four and struck out six.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/chicago/cubs/post/_/id/37791/jake-arrieta-no-hits-reds-in-blowout-win-for-the-cubs |title=Jake Arrieta no-hits Reds in blowout win for the Cubs |website=ESPN.com|accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref> Arrieta, who at the time of the no-hitter had not recorded a loss in his previous 17 regular-season starts, became only the second MLB pitcher ever to go unbeaten in regular-season play between no-hitters, with the only other being [[Johnny Vander Meer]], who threw consecutive no-hitters in 1938.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/117068/jake-arrieta-in-a-league-of-his-own-when-it-comes-to-numbers-no-hitters |title=Jake Arrieta in a league of his own when it comes to numbers, no-hitters |website=ESPN.com |date=April 21, 2016 |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref>  The [[2016 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]] defeated Arrieta and the Cubs 3\u20132 on June 5, even with 12 strikeouts in his first five innings, stopping a 20-game regular season winning streak and giving him his first loss in 11 months.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuc |first=Chris |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/ct-jake-arrieta-win-sreak-ends-spt-0606-20160605-story.html |title=Jake Arrieta's 20-game winning streak ends on strange Sunday at Wrigley |work=Chicago Tribune |date=June 5, 2016 |accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he was 18\u20138 with a 3.10 ERA (10th in the NL) in {{frac|197|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 />  He led the league for the second consecutive year with 6.294 hits per 9 innings pitched, his 18 wins were third in the league, his .692 win-loss percentage was sixth, his 1.084 walks plus hits per innings pitched and 0.730 [[home run]]s per 9 innings pitched were seventh, his 190 strikeouts and {{frac|197|1|3}} innings pitched were eighth, and his 8.666 strikeouts per 9 innings pitched were tenth.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He won a [[Silver Slugger Award]] after batting .262/.304/.415 with 2 home runs and 7 [[RBI]]s in 65 at bats, and came in ninth in voting for the 2016 NL Cy Young Award.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nIn Game 3 of the [[2016 NLDS]], Arrieta hit a three-run home run off of [[San Francisco Giants]]' pitcher [[Madison Bumgarner]], the first time that a pitcher hit a home run off Bumgarner, which ended Bumgarner's consecutive playoff scoreless innings streak of over 24 innings. Arrieta won Game 2 and Game 6 of the [[2016 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=17950126 |title=Arrieta keeps Indians in check as Cubs force Game 7 |date= |website=ESPN.com |publisher= |accessdate=November 3, 2016 }}</ref> The Cubs won Game 7 of the series 8\u20137 in 10 innings, giving them their first World Series title after a 108-year drought.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bastian|first1=Jordan|last2=Muskat|first2=Carrie|title=Chicago Cubs win 2016 World Series|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/207938228/chicago-cubs-win-2016-world-series/|publisher=MLB|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\n\nOn January 13, 2017, he agreed to a contract for the 2017 baseball season. He was NL Pitcher of the Month in August.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nIn 2017, Arrieta made 30 starts with a 14\u201310 record and a 3.53 ERA (eighth in the National League) in {{frac|168|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He threw 14 [[wild pitch]]es, tied for most in the National League, his 10 hit by pitch were 5th in the NL, and his 8.020 hits per 9 innings pitched and 1.218 walks plus hits per 9 innings pitched were tenth in the league.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The Cubs finished the season 92\u201370 and clinched another NL Central division title.\n\nArrieta started Game four of the [[2017 NLDS]] and, after 90 pitches, left in the fourth inning trailing 1\u20130. The Cubs and Arrieta lost that game to the [[2017 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]] but won Game Five and moved on to the [[2017 NLCS]]. After three losses and facing elimination, Arrieta was the starter and winning pitcher in a Game Four victory against the [[2017 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]]. After the Cubs season ended in a Game Five loss to the Dodgers, Arrieta declined the Cubs' $17.4 million qualifying offer and became a [[free agent]] for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportingnews.com/au/mlb/news/mlb-free-agents-2017-18-jake-arrieta-brewers-rumors-potential-teams/b0bg6yvq2lu31dho7fsnjvg3x | title=MLB free agents 2017\u201318: Why Brewers could push hard for Jake Arrieta | work=Sporting News | author=Garcia, Cat | date=November 22, 2017 | accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies (2018\u2013present)===\n====2018====\nOn March 11, 2018, Arrieta agreed to a three-year, $75 million contract with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/phillies/news/phillies-sign-cy-young-winner-jake-arrieta/c-268457880|title=Phillies sign Arrieta to multiyear deal|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|work=MLB.com|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> He tore [[cartilage]] in his left knee in June, but did not tell the front office and was 1-5 with a 6.35 ERA over his last nine starts.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/phillies/jake-arrieta-reveals-root-knee-injury-expresses-optimism-manny-machado-bryce-harper-front Jake Arrieta reveals root of knee injury, expresses optimism on Manny Machado-Bryce Harper front | NBC Sports Philadelphia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For the season, he was 10\u201311 with a 3.96 ERA in {{frac|172|2|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He was second in the league in wild pitches (11), second among NL pitchers in errors (4), and third in the NL in salary ($30 million).<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He had the highest [[ground ball]] percentage among National League pitchers (51.6%), and induced a career-high 22 ground ball [[double play]]s, tied for 6th-most in Major League Baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=14,d|title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Dashboard - FanGraphs Baseball|website=www.fangraphs.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.mlb.com/player/jake-arrieta-453562?season=2019&team=143 Jake Arrieta Stats, Fantasy & News | MLB.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For the fourth consecutive season he made 30 or more  starts, one of seven NL pitchers to do so in that time period.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> On defense, he had the lowest [[fielding percentage]] of all major league pitchers with 170 or more innings pitched, at .862.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=p&stats=fld&lg=all&qual=170&type=0&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=21,a|title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Fielding Statistics - FanGraphs Baseball|website=www.fangraphs.com}}</ref> After the 2018 season concluded, he was sixth of all active pitchers in career hits per 9 innings pitched (7.551).<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n====2019====\nIn January 2019, he had an [[MRI]] on his injured left knee and a surgical procedure to clean up the [[meniscus (anatomy)|meniscus]] in his knee.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>[http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25989900/phillies-jake-arrieta-recovering-recent-knee-surgery Phillies' Jake Arrieta recovering after recent knee surgery<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On August 17 it was announced that Arrieta would have season-ending surgery to remove a [[bone spur]] in his right pitching elbow.<ref name=autogenerated5>[https://www.si.com/mlb/2019/08/17/jake-arrieta-phillies-elbow-surgery-season-ending \"Phillies SP Jake Arrieta to Undergo Season-Ending Elbow Surgery\"]</ref> In 2019 he was 8-8 with a 4.64 ERA, and 110 strikeouts in 135.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\nThrough 2019, Arrieta was 8th of all active pitchers in career hits-per-9-innings-pitched, at 7.767.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/arrieja01.shtml |title=Jake Arrieta Stats |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n== Pitching style ==\nArrieta throws five different pitches. He throws a [[four-seam fastball]], [[two-seam fastball]], [[Slider (baseball)|slider]]/[[cutter (baseball)|cutter]], [[curveball]], and a [[changeup]]. His fastball averages around 93\u201394&nbsp;mph, sometimes reaching upper-90s mph. He relies on ground balls and swinging strikes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=24037 |title=The Buyer's Guide Jake Arrieta |author=Breen, J. P. |publisher=[[Baseball Prospectus]] |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> His slider averages {{convert|88|mph}} with late break peaking out at {{convert|92|mph}} and his curve sits at {{convert|80|mph}} with two-plane break.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/jake-arrietas-one-grip-multi-slider/ |title=Jake Arrieta's One-Grip Multi-Slider |author=Eno Sarris |date=March 18, 2015 |accessdate=September 15, 2015 |publisher=[[Fangraphs]]}}</ref> His changeup has tailing motion like a [[two-seam fastball]] and ranges from {{convert|86|to|89|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Player Card: Jake Arrieta |url=http://www.brooksbaseball.net/landing.php?player=453562 |accessdate=July 18, 2014 |publisher=Brooks Baseball}}</ref> Arrieta noticeably pitches across his body.\n\n== Personal life ==\nArrieta lives in [[Austin, Texas]], during the [[offseason]] with his wife, Brittany, and their two children.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/102853448/family-matters-chicago-cubs-pitcher-jake-arrieta-doesnt-prepare-alone |title=Family matters: Arrieta doesn't prepare alone |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |author=Muskat, Carrie |date=December 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> He is known as a \"workout freak\" and uses [[cross-training]] in his workouts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/150865898/jake-arrieta-strong-despite-high-innings-total |title='Workout freak' Arrieta only getting stronger |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |author=Rogers, Phil |date=September 22, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Arrieta does [[pilates]] and incorporates [[Vegetable juice|kale juice]], [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]], and [[fruits]] into his diet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/ct-cubs-jake-arrieta-workout-routine-spt-0209-20160208-story.html |title=Jake Arrieta preparing for heavy workload, but Cubs would be fine with less |work=Chicago Tribune |date=February 8, 2016 |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |author=Gonzales, Mark}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/cubs-jake-arrieta-changing-diet-workout-routine/ |publisher=CBS Sports |title=Cubs' Jake Arrieta changing diet, workout routine |date=March 28, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |author=Krest, Shawn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/ct-jake-arrieta-cubs-spring-training-spt-0329-20150328-story.html |title=Cubs' Jake Arrieta believes healthier diet will pay off during season |work=Chicago Tribune |author=Gonzales, Mark |date=March 28, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Arrieta's maternal grandfather is of [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] ancestry.<ref name=\"Mooney\">{{cite web|last1=Mooney|first1=Patrick|title=Jake Arrieta explains post-election tweet and why he will miss White House trip with Cubs|url=http://www.nbcsports.com/chicago/chicago-cubs/jake-arrieta-explains-post-election-tweet-and-why-he-will-miss-white-house-trip-cubs|publisher=NBC Sports Chicago|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Arrieta served as a groomsman for former TCU teammate [[Matt Carpenter (baseball)|Matt Carpenter]]'s wedding on December 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muskat |first1=Carrie |last2=Langosch |first2=Jenifer |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/153689556/jake-arrieta-matt-carpenter-bonded-in-college |title=Arrieta\u2013Carpenter bond faces playoff test: Stomping grounds: Friends always pushed each other in college |website=MLB.com |date=October 10, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Arrieta appeared in the [[HBO]] television show ''[[Veep]]'', alongside Orioles teammate [[Tommy Hunter (baseball)|Tommy Hunter]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/cubs-reunite-veep-castmates-jake-arrieta-and-tommy-hunter/ | title=Cubs reunite \u2018Veep\u2019 castmates Jake Arrieta and Tommy Hunter | publisher=Chicago Sun Times | date=June 24, 2016 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Thele, Kyle}}</ref> In 2017, Arrieta appeared in an episode of ''[[Chicago Fire (TV series)|Chicago Fire]]'' alongside Cubs teammate [[Kris Bryant]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chicago-fire-chicago-cubs-kris-bryant-jake-arrieta-guest-star-993358 | title='Chicago Fire' Taps Chicago Cubs All-Stars for Season 5 Finale | publisher=The Hollywood Reporter | date=April 12, 2017 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Stanhope, Kate}}</ref>\n\n== Accomplishments and awards ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:auto;\" center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccf;\" | Award/Honor\n! style=\"background:#ccf;\" | Date\n! style=\"background:#ccf;\" | Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''Major League Accomplishments & Awards'''\n|-\n| [[List of Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitchers|Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitcher]]\n| April 4, 2016\n| <ref name=2016OpeningDay />\n|-\n| [[Cy Young Award|National League Cy Young Award]]\n| 2015\n| <ref name=CyYoungESPN>{{cite web |last=Rogers |first=Jesse |title=Jake Arrieta wins NL Cy Young to continue Cubs' awards run |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/14165080/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-wins-national-league-cy-young-award |work=ESPN |date=November 18, 2015 |accessdate=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of Major League Baseball annual wins leaders|MLB Wins Leader]]\n| 2015\n| <ref name=CyYoungESPN />\n|-\n| Pitched a [[no-hitter]]\n| August 30, 2015; April 21, 2016\n| <ref name=AwardAugust2105 />\n|-\n| [[Major League Baseball Pitcher of the Month|National League Pitcher of the Month]]\n| 2015 (August & September); 2016 (April); 2017 (August)\n| <ref name=AwardAugust2105 /><ref name=AwardSeptember2015 />\n|-\n| [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week|National League Player of the Week]]\n| 2015 (July 6\u201312, August 24\u201330, & September 21\u201327)\n| <ref name=AwardLastWeekAugust2015 />\n|-\n| [[List of Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitchers|Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitcher]]\n| April 5, 2012\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2015/04/06/every-baltimore-orioles-opening-day-starter-result/ |title=Every Baltimore Orioles Opening Day Starter & Result |publisher=CBS Baltimore |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''Minor League Accomplishments & Awards'''\n|-\n| [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] Pitcher of the Week\n| 2009 (May 18\u201324 & June 8\u201314)\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile>{{cite web |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/player/453562/jake-arrieta |title=Jake Arrieta MLB Profile |publisher=MLB |date=2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[All-Star Futures Game]]\n| 2008\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/9085128/9085595 |title=Rosters for Futures Game 2008 official |publisher=CBS Sports |date=June 28, 2008 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Carolina League]] Pitcher of the Year\n| 2008\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| Carolina League Postseason All-Star\n| 2008\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| Carolina League Mid-Season All-Star\n| 2008\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/minors/carolina-league-takes-midseason-showdown/ |title=Carolina League Takes Midseason Showdown |publisher=Baseball America |author=Rode, Nathan |date=June 27, 2008 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Carolina League Pitcher of the Week\n| 2008 (May 12\u201318 & May 26 \u2013 June 1)\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| [[Arizona Fall League]] All-Prospect Team\n| 2007\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''College Baseball Accomplishments & Awards'''\n|-\n| [[Baseball America]] Second-Team All-American\n| 2006\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/college/awards/all-america-teams/2006/261703.html |title=2006 College All-America Team |publisher=Baseball America |date=June 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |author=Fit, Aaron}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[NCBWA]] second-team All-American\n| 2006\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/ncbwa/news/2006/allamerica060613.pdf |title=NCBWA ANNOUNCES 2006 PRO-LINE CAP/NCBWA DIVISION I ALL-AMERICA TEAMS |publisher=NCBWA |date=June 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2006 NCAA Division I baseball season|NCAA Division I baseball]] Wins leader\n| 2006\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/baseball_RB/2010/D1.pdf |title=Division I Baseball Records |publisher=NCAA |date=2010 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Mountain West Conference]] Co-Pitcher of the Year\n| 2006\n| <ref name=\"TCU Bio\" />\n|-\n| First-team All-Mountain West\n| 2006 & 2007\n| <ref name=\"TCU Bio\" />\n|-\n| Mountain West Conference Pitcher of the Week\n| 2006 (Feb. 13\u201319, May 8\u201314, May 22\u201328)\n| <ref name=\"TCU Bio\" />\n|-\n| [[Houston College Classic]] All-Tournament team\n| 2006\n| <ref name=\"TCU Bio\" />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''Other'''\n|-\n| [[Best Breakthrough Athlete ESPY Award]]\n| 2016\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Stephen Curry, Jake Arrieta collect first awards at ESPYS|url=http://espn.go.com/espys/2016/story/_/id/17061236/2016-espy-awards|website=ESPN|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jake Arrieta}}\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=453562|espn=30145|br=a/arrieja01|fangraphs=4153|brm=arriet001jak|retro=A/Parrij001}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/95cae16c Jake Arrieta] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=arrieja01 Jake Arrieta] at Baseball Almanac]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Jake Arrieta\u2014awards and honors\n| list1 =\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Jeremy Guthrie]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n|title=[[List of Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitchers|Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitcher]]\n| years=2012\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Jason Hammel]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Jon Lester]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n|title=[[List of Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitchers|Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitcher]]\n| years=2016\n}}\n{{s-aft\n|after= [[Jon Lester]]\n}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[National League]] [[Major League Baseball Pitcher of the Month Award|Pitcher of the Month]]\n| years = August\u2013September 2015<br />April 2016\n| before = [[Clayton Kershaw]]\n| after = [[Kyle Hendricks]]<br />[[Iv\u00e1n Nova]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[National League]] [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]]\n| years = July 6\u201312, 2015<br />August 24\u201330, 2015<br />September 21\u20137, 2015\n| before = [[Aramis Ram\u00edrez]]<br />[[A. J. Pollock]]<br />[[Stephen Strasburg]]\n| after = [[Zack Greinke]]<br />[[Bartolo Col\u00f3n]]<br />[[Max Scherzer]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title  = [[No-hitter]] pitcher\n| years  = August 30, 2015<br />April 21, 2016\n| before = [[Mike Fiers]]<br />[[Max Scherzer]]\n| after = [[Max Scherzer]]<br />[[Edinson V\u00f3lquez]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mountain West Conference Baseball Pitcher of the Year navbox}}\n{{NL Cy Young}}\n{{NL P Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{NL wins champions}}\n{{Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{United States baseball roster 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n{{2016 Chicago Cubs}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arrieta, Jake}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Bowie Baysox players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cy Young Award winners]]\n[[Category:Daytona Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Frederick Keys players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:National League wins champions]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Tides players]]\n[[Category:Olympic baseball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in baseball]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Desert Dogs players]]\n[[Category:Plano East Senior High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Plano, Texas]]\n[[Category:TCU Horned Frogs baseball players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Smokies players]]\n[[Category:Weatherford Coyotes baseball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Jake Arrieta\n| image         = Jake Arrieta (47501185272) (cropped).jpg\n| caption       = Arrieta with the Phillies in 2019\n| team          = Philadelphia Phillies\n| number        = 49\n| position      = [[Pitcher]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1986|3|6}}\n| birth_place   = [[Farmington, Missouri|Farmington]], [[Missouri]]\n| bats          = Right\n| throws        = Right\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = June 10\n| debutyear     = 2010\n| debutteam     = Baltimore Orioles\n| statyear      = 2019 season\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n| stat1value    = 106\u201375\n| stat2label    = [[Earned run average]]\n| stat2value    = 3.72\n| stat3label    = [[Strikeout]]s\n| stat3value    = 1,318\n| teams         =\n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2013}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n| awards        =\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2016 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2016]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2016}})\n* [[Cy Young Award|NL Cy Young Award]] (2015)\n* [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2016)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual wins leaders|MLB wins leader]] (2015)\n* Pitched two [[no-hitter]]s (2015, 2016)\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Baseball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Baseball at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[World University Baseball Championship|2006 Havana]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Jacob Joseph Arrieta''' (born March 6, 1986) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[Chicago Cubs]]. \n\nArrieta played college baseball at [[Weatherford College|Weatherford Junior College]] and at [[Texas Christian University]] (TCU). He was an All\u2013American and was named Mountain West Conference Pitcher of the Year at TCU. The Orioles selected Arrieta in the fifth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft|2007 MLB draft]], and he signed a then record contract for a fifth round draft pick. He pitched for the [[United States national baseball team]] at the [[Baseball at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Olympics]], winning the [[bronze medal]]. \n\nHe made his big league debut for the Orioles in 2010, and after four seasons Arrieta was traded to the Cubs in 2013. In 2015, Arrieta led MLB in wins with 22, pitched a [[no-hitter]], and won the 2015 National League [[Cy Young Award]]. In 2016, he was an NL [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All Star]], threw his second no-hitter, was awarded a [[Silver Slugger Award]], and won a [[2016 World Series|World Series]] with the Cubs. \n\nPrior to the start of the 2018 season, Arrieta signed a three-year, $75 million contract as a free agent with the Phillies. In August 2019 it was announced that he would have season-ending surgery to remove a [[bone spur]] in his pitching elbow.\n\n== Amateur career ==\n\nArrieta was born in [[Farmington, Missouri]], to Lou and Lynda Arrieta.<ref name=\"STLtoday\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stltoday.com/sports/columns/benjamin-hochman/hochman-cubs-fan-just-can-t-help-it-even-in/article_cd225980-5c45-5331-9c22-80e3b2510bf5.html | title=Cubs fan just can't help it, even in Cardinals territory | publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch | date=September 23, 2016 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Hochman, Benjamin}}</ref> They moved to Texas four months after Arrieta was born, and he grew up in [[Plano, Texas]], where he attended [[Plano East Senior High School]].<ref name=\"STLtoday\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/community/weatherford-star-telegram/wt-sports/article46195340.html|title=Former Weatherford Coyote wins Cy Young Award|website=star-telegram}}</ref> He was 6\u20131 with a 1.61 ERA as a junior, and 5\u20134 with a 1.30 ERA as a senior.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://gofrogs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=331|title=Jake Arrieta - Baseball|website=TCU Athletics}}</ref> As a high school senior he was selected by the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in the 31st round of the [[2004 Major League Baseball draft|2004 draft]], but instead he chose to attend college.<ref name=\"TCU Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gofrogs.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/arrieta_jake00.html |title=Jake Arrieta |publisher=TCU Athletics |access-date=August 31, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809040439/http://www.gofrogs.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/arrieta_jake00.html |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1818294#rd31 |title=MLB 2004 Draft selections, Day 2 |publisher=ESPN |date=June 8, 2004 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nArrieta attended [[Weatherford College|Weatherford Junior College]] for his freshman year in 2005, posting a 6\u20132 [[win\u2013loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] with a 3.43 ERA.<ref name=\"TCU Bio\" /> Following his freshman year, Arrieta was selected by the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] in the 26th round of the [[2005 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nInstead, he opted to transfer to [[Texas Christian University]] (TCU), where he played for the [[TCU Horned Frogs baseball|TCU Horned Frogs baseball team]] for his sophomore and junior seasons, and studied [[sport psychology]].<ref name=\"TCU Bio\" /><ref name=\"sport psych\" /> During the summer of 2005, prior to enrolling at TCU, Arrieta participated in summer collegiate baseball with the McKinney Marshalls of the [[Texas Collegiate League]], and posted a 4\u20133 record in 10 starts with a 1.87 ERA over {{frac|62|2|3}} [[inning]]s pitched.<ref name=\"TCU Bio\" /> During his sophomore year in 2006, Arrieta led [[college baseball]] with 14 wins and had a 2.35 ERA over 19 appearances, and he had 111 [[strikeout]]s in 111 innings.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref name=\"sport psych\">{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/110014572/strong-body-and-mind-fuel-cubs-jake-arrieta |publisher=MLB.com |title=Strong body and mind fuel Cubs' Arrieta |author=Muskat, Carrie |date=February 22, 2015 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> He won the [[Mountain West Conference]] Pitcher of the Year Award and was named a [[College Baseball All-America Team|Second-Team College Baseball All-American]] after his sophomore year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gofrogs.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/111506aaa.html |title=Arrieta named NCBWA preseason 1st-team All-American |publisher=TCU Athletics |date=November 15, 2006 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nin his junior year in 2007, he was 9\u20133 with a 3.01 ERA.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He was named First-team All-Mountain West in 2007.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nArrieta first joined the [[United States national baseball team]] in 2006, and helped the team win the [[World University Baseball Championship]] in [[Cuba]]. He was 4\u20130 with 34 strikeouts and a 0.27 ERA\u2014allowing just one [[earned run]] in 35 innings pitched over six starts for the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gofrogs.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/arrieta_jake00.html |title=TCU Athletics |accessdate=August 18, 2008}}</ref> In his first start at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing, Arrieta pitched six innings and struck out seven in Team USA's 9\u20131 victory over the [[China national baseball team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080818&content_id=3328463&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=More tension than expected in U.S. win |accessdate=August 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\n\n=== Draft and minors ===\n[[File:Jake Arrieta on August 8, 2009, Futures at Fenway.jpg|200px|thumb|Arrieta pitching for the [[Norfolk Tides]] in 2009]]\nThe [[Baltimore Orioles]] selected Arrieta in the fifth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]]. He signed with the Orioles for a $1.1&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]], which at the time was the largest signing bonus for a fifth round draft pick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/stats/stats.jsp?n=Jake%20Arrieta&pos=P&sid=milb&t=p_pbp&pid=453562 |title=Minor League Baseball |accessdate=August 18, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://starlocalmedia.com/planocourier/sports/arrieta-to-live-olympic-dream/article_68bbfcbb-f569-5cdc-bed9-d07350b93086.html |title=Arrieta To Live Olympic Dream |work=Plano Star Courier |date=August 7, 2008 |accessdate=August 31, 2015 |author=O'Brien, Ben}}</ref><ref name=\"WT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/blog/national-pastime/2008/jun/5/prospect-qa---jake-arrieta-baltimore-orioles/ |work=Washington Times |title=Prospect Q ;amp& A: Jake Arrieta, Orioles |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=LeBlanc, Jay}}</ref>\n\nArrieta made his professional debut in the [[Arizona Fall League]] with the [[Phoenix Desert Dogs]] in 2007. He posted 16 scoreless innings, while striking out 16 over 14 appearances, and helped lead the Desert Dogs to the Arizona League championship.<ref name=\"WT\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://napavalleyregister.com/sports/another-banner-year-for-desert-dogs/article_aa6db25e-e40e-586e-9c58-634181ccff63.html |title=Another banner year for Desert Dogs |date=November 24, 2007 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |publisher=Napa Valley Register |author=Miller, Harrell}}</ref>\n\nArrieta pitched to a 6\u20135 record with a 2.87 ERA and 120 strikeouts over 113 innings for the [[Frederick Keys]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Carolina League]] when his season ended in order to allow him to play for the [[United States at the 2008 Summer Olympics|USA Baseball team]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baseball.realgm.com/analysis/569/Prospect-Report-Jake-Arrieta-Baltimore-Orioles |title=Prospect Report: Jake Arrieta, Baltimore Orioles |publisher=RealGM |author=Reina, Christopher |date=March 9, 2009 |accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.njcaa.org/sports/bsb/2007-08/releases/2008-07-25_6797.html |publisher=NJCAA |date=July 25, 2008 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |title=Two Former NJCAA Baseball Players Named to USA Olympic Team}}</ref>\n\n===Baltimore Orioles (2010\u20132013)===\n[[File:Jake Arrieta 2011.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Arrieta pitching for the Orioles in 2011]]\nArrieta made his major league debut on June 10, 2010, against the [[New York Yankees]] at [[Oriole Park at Camden Yards|Camden Yards]]. He pitched six innings, giving up four hits and three runs, [[strikeout|striking out]] six and earning the win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100610&content_id=11036810&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=bal |title=O's Arrieta beats Yankees in MLB debut |work=Baltimore Orioles |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> For the 2010 season, he was 6\u20136 with a 4.66 ERA in {{frac|100|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/arrieja01.shtml|title=Jake Arrieta Stats|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nHe won the home opener for the Orioles in 2011, and was the youngest opening day starting pitcher for the Orioles since [[Mike Mussina]] in 1994.<ref name=\"CT\">{{cite web | url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/ct-jake-arrieta-cubs-giants-haugh-spt-0810-20150809-column.html | title=Cubs are for real, and so is Jake Arrieta, the ace of their pitching staff | publisher=Chicago Tribune | date=August 5, 2019 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Haugh, David}}</ref> In 2011, he was 10\u20138 with a 5.05 ERA in {{frac|113|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Arrieta was again named the opening day starter for the Orioles in 2012. After starting the 2012 season 3\u20139 with an ERA of 6.13, Arrieta was demoted to Triple-A on July 6, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/team/transactions.jsp?c_id=bal#month=7&year=2012&team_id=110%7ctitle=MLB.com |title=Transactions |work=Baltimore Orioles |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nArrieta began the 2013 season with four starts for the Orioles posting a 1\u20131 record and a 6.63 ERA until being sent down to the Triple-A [[Norfolk Tides]] on April 22 after the Orioles recalled [[Alex Burnett]].<ref name=\"USATODAY2013\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/orioles/2013/06/14/orioles-recall-jake-arrieta-option-kevin-gausman/2425113/ |work=USA Today |title=Orioles option rookie Gausman, recall Arrieta |date=June 14, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlbdailydish.com/2013/4/22/4253904/orioles-demote-jake-arrieta-recall-alex-burnett |publisher=SB Nation |title=Orioles demote Jake Arrieta to Triple-A, recall Alex Burnett |date=April 22, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=Aderhold, Nathan}}</ref> He was recalled by the Orioles on May 18 and later optioned back down to Triple-A to make room for [[Kevin Gausman]] on May 23.<ref name=\"USATODAY2013\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-05-24/sports/bs-sp-orioles-notes-0524-20130523_1_jake-arrieta-triple-a-norfolk-kevin-gausman |title=Jake Arrieta sent back to Triple-A to make room for Gausman |work=Baltimore Sun |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=Encina, Eduardo}}</ref> He was recalled again on June 14 and Gausman was optioned to Triple-A to make room on the roster for Arrieta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-06-14/sports/bal-pregame-orioles-notes-gausman-arrieta-hammel-reimold-draft-picks-20130614_1_kevin-gausman-triple-a-norfolk-orioles-notes |title=Orioles notes: Gausman not guaranteed to return to majors soon |work=Baltimore Sun |date=June 14, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |author=Connolly, Dan}}</ref> In 2013 with Baltimore, he was 1\u20132 with a 7.23 ERA in {{frac|23|2|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Through four years with the Orioles, Arrieta posted a record of 20\u201325 and a 5.46 ERA in 358 innings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/02/orioles-trade-cubs-dodgers-marmol_n_3537086.html |publisher=Huffington Post |date=July 2, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2016 |title=Orioles Trade Jake Arrieta, Pedro Strop To Cubs, Who Shipped Carlos Marmol To Dodgers |author=Gonzalez, Anthony}}</ref>\n\n=== Chicago Cubs (2013\u20132017) ===\n\n==== 2013 ====\nOn July 2, 2013, the Orioles traded Arrieta along with [[Pedro Strop]] to the [[Chicago Cubs]] for [[Scott Feldman]] and [[Steve Clevenger]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Drew |title=Orioles Trade Jake Arrieta and Pedro Strop to Cubs for Scott Feldman |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1691801-orioles-trade-jake-arrieta-and-pedro-stropm-to-cubs-for-scott-feldman |website=bleacherreport.com |publisher=bleacher report |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>  He was optioned to the [[Iowa Cubs]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[Pacific Coast League]] upon being acquired. After making 5 starts for Iowa, Arrieta was recalled to start Game 2 of a doubleheader against the Brewers on July 30. In his Chicago debut, he gave up 1 run in 6 innings, earning a no-decision in the 3\u20132 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_07_30_milmlb_chnmlb_2&mode=recap_home&c_id=chc |title=Cubs falter after Arrieta's strong debut |work=MLB.com |first=Manny |last=Randhawa |date=July 31, 2013}}</ref> After the game, Arrieta was optioned to Iowa where he made two more starts before being recalled on August 14 to replace [[Carlos Villanueva (baseball)|Carlos Villanueva]] in the rotation. He made eight more starts before the end of the season. In his nine starts with Chicago, he went 4\u20132 with a 3.66 ERA, striking out 37 in {{frac|51|2|3}} innings. In 30 games (29 starts) in 2013 including the minors, Arrieta went 12\u20139 with a 4.42 ERA, striking out 137 in {{frac|154|2|3}} innings.\n\n==== 2014 ====\nArrieta took no-hitters into the seventh or eighth innings three times in the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Phil |title=Arrieta looks like pitching cornerstone for Cubs |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/95183312/phil-rogers-jake-arrieta-looks-like-pitching-cornerstone-for-cubs |publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=September 18, 2014}}</ref> On June 24, Arrieta retired the first 18 Reds in order, but the perfect game was broken up by Cincinnati's [[Billy Hamilton (baseball, born 1990)|Billy Hamilton]]'s leadoff double in the seventh. On June 30, against the Red Sox, Arrieta took a no-hitter into the 8th until [[Stephen Drew]] singled with two outs the inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=340630102 |title=Jake Arrieta takes no-hit bid into 8th as Cubs blank Red Sox |publisher=ESPN |date=August 1, 2014 |accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2014 season, he posted a 10\u20135 record with a 2.53 ERA, and in {{frac|156|2|3}} innings he gave up 114 hits, walked 41, and struck out 167.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He came in 9th in voting for the National League [[Cy Young Award]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==== 2015 ====\nOn July 12, 2015, Arrieta pitched a [[complete game]] victory over the Chicago White Sox at Wrigley Field, his second complete game of the season and the third of his major league career.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muskat |last2=Garno |first1=Carrie |first2=Greg |title=Arrieta goes distance, goes deep in 10th win |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/136293868/jake-arrieta-dominates-white-sox-for-10th-win |work=MLB.com |date=July 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jake Arrieta masterful as Cubs avoid sweep vs. White Sox |url=http://www.csnchicago.com/cubs/jake-arrieta-masterful-cubs-avoid-sweep-vs-white-sox |archive-url=https://archive.today/20151117055959/http://www.csnchicago.com/cubs/jake-arrieta-masterful-cubs-avoid-sweep-vs-white-sox |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 17, 2015 |work=[[Comcast SportsNet Chicago|CSNChicago.com]] |date=July 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 12, 2015 }}</ref> On August 20, Arrieta became the first MLB pitcher to win 15 games in the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowman |last2=Muskat |first1=Mark |first2=Carrie |title=Arrieta first to 15 wins as Cubs rout Braves |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/144338294/jake-arrieta-wins-15th-as-cubs-rout-braves |work=MLB.com |date=August 21, 2015 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Ten days later, Arrieta [[no-hitter|no-hit]] the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] at [[Dodger Stadium]] for the [[List of Chicago Cubs no-hitters|14th no-hitter in Cubs history]]. He struck out 12 batters, including all three batters he faced in both the first and ninth innings. [[Sandy Koufax]] had been the last pitcher to complete a no-hitter by striking out all three batters he faced in the ninth inning, doing so against the Cubs in [[Sandy Koufax's perfect game|his 1965 perfect game]]\u2014a game also played at Dodger Stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/chicago-cubs-los-angeles-dodgers-350830119/ |title=Chi Cubs at LA Dodgers \u2013 2015-08-30 \u2013 Major League Baseball \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |date=August 31, 2015 |work=Yahoo! Sports |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> Arrieta was named the [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|NL Player of the Week]] for August 24\u201330 and [[Major League Baseball Pitcher of the Month Award|NL Pitcher of the Month]] for August with a 6\u20130 and a 0.43 ERA and the no-hitter. The right-hander held opposing hitters to a .130 batting average and a .196 on-base percentage in August and struck out 43 batters while walking just 10.<ref name=AwardLastWeekAugust2015>{{cite web |last=Press release |title=Jake Arrieta of the Chicago Cubs named National League Player of the Week |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146492750 |work=MLB.com |date=September 3, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=AwardAugust2105>{{cite web |last=Fordin |first=Spencer |title=Arrieta named NL Pitcher of the Month: Right-hander goes 6\u20130 with 0.43 ERA in August, capping month with no-hitter |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/147184218 |work=MLB.com |date=September 3, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>  On September 22, Arrieta won his 20th game of the season, throwing a three-hitter against the Brewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/151016074 |title=Arrieta, Bryant make history in Cubs' win |accessdate=September 23, 2015 |last1=Garno |first1=Greg |last2=Jackson |first2=John |date=September 22, 2015 |work=[[MLB]]}}</ref>  With 11 more strikeouts in that 4\u20130 Cubs victory at Wrigley, he was the first MLB pitcher to win 20 games this season and had his fourth complete game and third shutout of the season.\n\nAfter the 2015 All-Star break, he gave up 9 earned runs during 15 starts over {{frac|107|1|3}} innings for a 0.75 ERA, the lowest in MLB history in the second half.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/14165080/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-wins-national-league-cy-young-award |title=NL Cy Young winner Jake Arrieta finally put 'small things in place' |publisher=ESPN |author=Greenberg, Jon |date=November 19, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/eye-on-baseball/25325940/cubs-jake-arrieta-sets-all-time-mark-with-075-era-in-second-half |title=Cubs' Jake Arrieta sets record with 0.75 ERA in second half |publisher=CBS Sports |author=[[Dayn Perry|Perry, Dayn]] |date=October 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref> On October 5, he was again named NL Pitcher of the Month for his 4\u20130 September record with a 0.45 ERA.<ref name=AwardSeptember2015>{{cite web |title=Cubs superhuman ace Jake Arrieta wins consecutive NL Pitcher of the Month |url=http://www.csnchicago.com/cubs/cubs-superhuman-ace-jake-arrieta-wins-consecutive-nl-pitcher-month |website=csnchicago.com |publisher=CSN CHGO |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor the season, Arrieta's 22\u20136 record and 1.77 ERA (second in the NL) made him only the fifth pitcher to win at least 22 games with no more than six losses and a sub-2.00 ERA since the earned run became an official stat in 1913.<ref>Verducci, Tom [https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/03/28/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-profile The Revenant: How Jake Arrieta came back from the baseball dead] ''Sports Illustrated''. March 30, 2016</ref> Arrieta's 2015 season has been widely compared to [[Bob Gibson]]'s 1968 season in which Gibson won the National League MVP and Cy Young Awards after posting a [[live-ball era]] record 1.12 ERA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsworld.nbcsports.com/jake-arrieta-leads-cubs-past-pirates/ |title=CHANNELING BOB GIBSON |publisher=NBC Sports |date=October 8, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |author=[[Joe Posnanski|Posnanski, Joe]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/09/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-mlb |title=Cubs ace Jake Arrieta is 9\u20130 with a 0.48 ERA since the start of August |work=USA Today |author=Berg, Ted |date=September 23, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/997874/jake-arrieta-best-non-bob-gibson-19-game-stretch-era-since-1914 |title=Jake Arrieta has the second-best 19-game ERA since 1914 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |author=Ogden, Rob |date=September 29, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119235657/http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/997874/jake-arrieta-best-non-bob-gibson-19-game-stretch-era-since-1914 |archive-date=November 19, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He led the majors in wins, complete games (4), and [[shutout]]s (3), and led the National League in hits per 9 innings pitched (5.895) and games started (33).<ref name=autogenerated2 />  He also led the majors in lowest [[home runs per nine innings]] (0.39).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2015&month=0&season1=2015&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,a|title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2015 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Dashboard - FanGraphs Baseball|website=www.fangraphs.com}}</ref> His .786 win-loss percentage and his 0.865 [[walk]]s plus hits per innings pitched were second in the NL.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n[[File:Jake Arrieta does pushups.jpg|thumb|Jake Arrieta does pushups before his start in [[2015 National League Championship Series#Game 2|Game 2 of the 2015 NLCS]]]]\nArrieta started the [[2015 National League Wild Card Game]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Muskat |first=Carrie |title=Jake Arrieta to start NL wild card game |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/153200532/jake-arrieta-to-start-nl-wild-card-game |work=MLB.com |date=October 4, 2015 |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> He pitched a complete-game shutout, striking out 11 batters and allowed only four hits to defeat the Pittsburgh Pirates 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chc vs Pit 10/07/2015 Boxscore |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2015_10_07_chnmlb_pitmlb_1#game=2015_10_07_chnmlb_pitmlb_1,game_tab=box,game_state=Wrapup |website=mlb.mlb.com |publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref> He became the first pitcher to post a postseason shutout while striking out at least 10 batters and walking zero.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casella |first1=Paul |title=10 cool facts about Arrieta's Wild Card shutout |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/153648164/10-facts-from-jake-arrieta-in-wild-card-game |website=m.mlb.com |publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref> He is also the first pitcher to have more [[stolen base]]s than runs scored in a postseason game when he stole [[second base]] in the top of the 7th inning. Arrieta was the pitcher of record in the Game 2 loss of the [[2015 National League Championship Series]] to the New York Mets.\n\nArrieta won the [[NL Cy Young Award]] to become the first Cubs pitcher to do so since [[Greg Maddux]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Woo |first1=Jeremy |title=Dallas Keuchel, Jake Arrieta named AL, NL Cy Young Award winners |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/11/18/dallas-keuchel-jake-arrieta-cy-young-award-winners |website=si.com |publisher=Sports Illustratedsi.com |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>  He was the fifth Cubs winner overall, also joining [[Fergie Jenkins]] (1971), [[Bruce Sutter]] (1979) and [[Rick Sutcliffe]] (1984).<ref name=CyYoungESPN /> He also came in sixth in the voting for 2015 NL [[Most Valuable Player Award]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==== 2016 ====\n[[File:Cubs starter Jake Arrieta delivers a pitch in the first inning of World Series Game 6. (30634554251).jpg|thumb|left|Arrieta pitching in Game 6 of the [[2016 World Series]]]]\nOn February 5, 2016, Arrieta and the Cubs agreed on a record [[Salary arbitration|arbitration deal]] worth $10.7 million 2016 salary, the largest one-year contract for a second-time arbitration eligible pitcher, topping [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]]'s $10.1 million salary in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Dayn |title=Cubs Arrieta breaks record with $10.7 million dollar contract |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/eye-on-baseball/25475482/cubs-sign-jake-arrieta-to-107-million-contract-avoid-arbitration |website=cbssports.com |publisher=CBS Sports |accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref>  The club chose him as the [[2016 Chicago Cubs season|2016 season]] Opening Day starting pitcher against the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Angels]] on April 4.<ref name=2016OpeningDay>{{cite web | last = Muskat | first = Carrie | title = Arrieta carries great expectations into Opening Day | url = http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/169885240/cubs-jake-arrieta-ready-for-opening-day-start | work = MLB.com | date = April 1, 2016 | accessdate = April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, Arrieta pitched his second career no-hitter and the [[List of Chicago Cubs no-hitters|15th no-hitter in Cubs history]] against the Cincinnati Reds in a 16\u20130 blowout win.  He walked four and struck out six.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/chicago/cubs/post/_/id/37791/jake-arrieta-no-hits-reds-in-blowout-win-for-the-cubs |title=Jake Arrieta no-hits Reds in blowout win for the Cubs |website=ESPN.com|accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref> Arrieta, who at the time of the no-hitter had not recorded a loss in his previous 17 regular-season starts, became only the second MLB pitcher ever to go unbeaten in regular-season play between no-hitters, with the only other being [[Johnny Vander Meer]], who threw consecutive no-hitters in 1938.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/117068/jake-arrieta-in-a-league-of-his-own-when-it-comes-to-numbers-no-hitters |title=Jake Arrieta in a league of his own when it comes to numbers, no-hitters |website=ESPN.com |date=April 21, 2016 |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref>  The [[2016 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]] defeated Arrieta and the Cubs 3\u20132 on June 5, even with 12 strikeouts in his first five innings, stopping a 20-game regular season winning streak and giving him his first loss in 11 months.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuc |first=Chris |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/ct-jake-arrieta-win-sreak-ends-spt-0606-20160605-story.html |title=Jake Arrieta's 20-game winning streak ends on strange Sunday at Wrigley |work=Chicago Tribune |date=June 5, 2016 |accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he was 18\u20138 with a 3.10 ERA (10th in the NL) in {{frac|197|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 />  He led the league for the second consecutive year with 6.294 hits per 9 innings pitched, his 18 wins were third in the league, his .692 win-loss percentage was sixth, his 1.084 walks plus hits per innings pitched and 0.730 [[home run]]s per 9 innings pitched were seventh, his 190 strikeouts and {{frac|197|1|3}} innings pitched were eighth, and his 8.666 strikeouts per 9 innings pitched were tenth.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He won a [[Silver Slugger Award]] after batting .262/.304/.415 with 2 home runs and 7 [[RBI]]s in 65 at bats, and came in ninth in voting for the 2016 NL Cy Young Award.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nIn Game 3 of the [[2016 NLDS]], Arrieta hit a three-run home run off of [[San Francisco Giants]]' pitcher [[Madison Bumgarner]], the first time that a pitcher hit a home run off Bumgarner, which ended Bumgarner's consecutive playoff scoreless innings streak of over 24 innings. Arrieta won Game 2 and Game 6 of the [[2016 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=17950126 |title=Arrieta keeps Indians in check as Cubs force Game 7 |date= |website=ESPN.com |publisher= |accessdate=November 3, 2016 }}</ref> The Cubs won Game 7 of the series 8\u20137 in 10 innings, giving them their first World Series title after a 108-year drought.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bastian|first1=Jordan|last2=Muskat|first2=Carrie|title=Chicago Cubs win 2016 World Series|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/207938228/chicago-cubs-win-2016-world-series/|publisher=MLB|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\n\nOn January 13, 2017, he agreed to a contract for the 2017 baseball season. He was NL Pitcher of the Month in August.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nIn 2017, Arrieta made 30 starts with a 14\u201310 record and a 3.53 ERA (eighth in the National League) in {{frac|168|1|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He threw 14 [[wild pitch]]es, tied for most in the National League, his 10 hit by pitch were 5th in the NL, and his 8.020 hits per 9 innings pitched and 1.218 walks plus hits per 9 innings pitched were tenth in the league.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The Cubs finished the season 92\u201370 and clinched another NL Central division title.\n\nArrieta started Game four of the [[2017 NLDS]] and, after 90 pitches, left in the fourth inning trailing 1\u20130. The Cubs and Arrieta lost that game to the [[2017 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]] but won Game Five and moved on to the [[2017 NLCS]]. After three losses and facing elimination, Arrieta was the starter and winning pitcher in a Game Four victory against the [[2017 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]]. After the Cubs season ended in a Game Five loss to the Dodgers, Arrieta declined the Cubs' $17.4 million qualifying offer and became a [[free agent]] for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportingnews.com/au/mlb/news/mlb-free-agents-2017-18-jake-arrieta-brewers-rumors-potential-teams/b0bg6yvq2lu31dho7fsnjvg3x | title=MLB free agents 2017\u201318: Why Brewers could push hard for Jake Arrieta | work=Sporting News | author=Garcia, Cat | date=November 22, 2017 | accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies (2018\u2013present)===\n====2018====\nOn March 11, 2018, Arrieta agreed to a three-year, $75 million contract with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/phillies/news/phillies-sign-cy-young-winner-jake-arrieta/c-268457880|title=Phillies sign Arrieta to multiyear deal|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|work=MLB.com|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> He tore [[cartilage]] in his left knee in June, but did not tell the front office and was 1-5 with a 6.35 ERA over his last nine starts.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/phillies/jake-arrieta-reveals-root-knee-injury-expresses-optimism-manny-machado-bryce-harper-front Jake Arrieta reveals root of knee injury, expresses optimism on Manny Machado-Bryce Harper front | NBC Sports Philadelphia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For the season, he was 10\u201311 with a 3.96 ERA in {{frac|172|2|3}} innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He was second in the league in wild pitches (11), second among NL pitchers in errors (4), and third in the NL in salary ($30 million).<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He had the highest [[ground ball]] percentage among National League pitchers (51.6%), and induced a career-high 22 ground ball [[double play]]s, tied for 6th-most in Major League Baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=14,d|title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Dashboard - FanGraphs Baseball|website=www.fangraphs.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.mlb.com/player/jake-arrieta-453562?season=2019&team=143 Jake Arrieta Stats, Fantasy & News | MLB.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For the fourth consecutive season he made 30 or more  starts, one of seven NL pitchers to do so in that time period.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> On defense, he had the lowest [[fielding percentage]] of all major league pitchers with 170 or more innings pitched, at .862.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=p&stats=fld&lg=all&qual=170&type=0&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=21,a|title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Fielding Statistics - FanGraphs Baseball|website=www.fangraphs.com}}</ref> After the 2018 season concluded, he was sixth of all active pitchers in career hits per 9 innings pitched (7.551).<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n====2019====\nIn January 2019, he had an [[MRI]] on his injured left knee and a surgical procedure to clean up the [[meniscus (anatomy)|meniscus]] in his knee.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>[http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25989900/phillies-jake-arrieta-recovering-recent-knee-surgery Phillies' Jake Arrieta recovering after recent knee surgery<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On August 17 it was announced that Arrieta would have season-ending surgery to remove a [[bone spur]] in his right pitching elbow.<ref name=autogenerated5>[https://www.si.com/mlb/2019/08/17/jake-arrieta-phillies-elbow-surgery-season-ending \"Phillies SP Jake Arrieta to Undergo Season-Ending Elbow Surgery\"]</ref> In 2019 he was 8-8 with a 4.64 ERA, and 110 strikeouts in 135.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\nThrough 2019, Arrieta was 8th of all active pitchers in career hits-per-9-innings-pitched, at 7.767.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/arrieja01.shtml |title=Jake Arrieta Stats |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n== Pitching style ==\nArrieta throws five different pitches. He throws a [[four-seam fastball]], [[two-seam fastball]], [[Slider (baseball)|slider]]/[[cutter (baseball)|cutter]], [[curveball]], and a [[changeup]]. His fastball averages around 93\u201394&nbsp;mph, sometimes reaching upper-90s mph. He relies on ground balls and swinging strikes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=24037 |title=The Buyer's Guide Jake Arrieta |author=Breen, J. P. |publisher=[[Baseball Prospectus]] |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> His slider averages {{convert|88|mph}} with late break peaking out at {{convert|92|mph}} and his curve sits at {{convert|80|mph}} with two-plane break.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/jake-arrietas-one-grip-multi-slider/ |title=Jake Arrieta's One-Grip Multi-Slider |author=Eno Sarris |date=March 18, 2015 |accessdate=September 15, 2015 |publisher=[[Fangraphs]]}}</ref> His changeup has tailing motion like a [[two-seam fastball]] and ranges from {{convert|86|to|89|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Player Card: Jake Arrieta |url=http://www.brooksbaseball.net/landing.php?player=453562 |accessdate=July 18, 2014 |publisher=Brooks Baseball}}</ref> Arrieta noticeably pitches across his body.\n\n== Personal life ==\nArrieta lives in [[Austin, Texas]], during the [[offseason]] with his wife, Brittany, and their two children.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/102853448/family-matters-chicago-cubs-pitcher-jake-arrieta-doesnt-prepare-alone |title=Family matters: Arrieta doesn't prepare alone |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |author=Muskat, Carrie |date=December 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> He is known as a \"workout freak\" and uses [[cross-training]] in his workouts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/150865898/jake-arrieta-strong-despite-high-innings-total |title='Workout freak' Arrieta only getting stronger |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |author=Rogers, Phil |date=September 22, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Arrieta does [[pilates]] and incorporates [[Vegetable juice|kale juice]], [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]], and [[fruits]] into his diet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/ct-cubs-jake-arrieta-workout-routine-spt-0209-20160208-story.html |title=Jake Arrieta preparing for heavy workload, but Cubs would be fine with less |work=Chicago Tribune |date=February 8, 2016 |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |author=Gonzales, Mark}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/cubs-jake-arrieta-changing-diet-workout-routine/ |publisher=CBS Sports |title=Cubs' Jake Arrieta changing diet, workout routine |date=March 28, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |author=Krest, Shawn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/ct-jake-arrieta-cubs-spring-training-spt-0329-20150328-story.html |title=Cubs' Jake Arrieta believes healthier diet will pay off during season |work=Chicago Tribune |author=Gonzales, Mark |date=March 28, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Arrieta's maternal grandfather is of [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] ancestry.<ref name=\"Mooney\">{{cite web|last1=Mooney|first1=Patrick|title=Jake Arrieta explains post-election tweet and why he will miss White House trip with Cubs|url=http://www.nbcsports.com/chicago/chicago-cubs/jake-arrieta-explains-post-election-tweet-and-why-he-will-miss-white-house-trip-cubs|publisher=NBC Sports Chicago|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Arrieta served as a groomsman for former TCU teammate [[Matt Carpenter (baseball)|Matt Carpenter]]'s wedding on December 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muskat |first1=Carrie |last2=Langosch |first2=Jenifer |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/153689556/jake-arrieta-matt-carpenter-bonded-in-college |title=Arrieta\u2013Carpenter bond faces playoff test: Stomping grounds: Friends always pushed each other in college |website=MLB.com |date=October 10, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Arrieta appeared in the [[HBO]] television show ''[[Veep]]'', alongside Orioles teammate [[Tommy Hunter (baseball)|Tommy Hunter]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/cubs-reunite-veep-castmates-jake-arrieta-and-tommy-hunter/ | title=Cubs reunite \u2018Veep\u2019 castmates Jake Arrieta and Tommy Hunter | publisher=Chicago Sun Times | date=June 24, 2016 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Thele, Kyle}}</ref> In 2017, Arrieta appeared in an episode of ''[[Chicago Fire (TV series)|Chicago Fire]]'' alongside Cubs teammate [[Kris Bryant]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chicago-fire-chicago-cubs-kris-bryant-jake-arrieta-guest-star-993358 | title='Chicago Fire' Taps Chicago Cubs All-Stars for Season 5 Finale | publisher=The Hollywood Reporter | date=April 12, 2017 | accessdate=February 14, 2019 | author=Stanhope, Kate}}</ref>\n\n== Accomplishments and awards ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:auto;\" center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccf;\" | Award/Honor\n! style=\"background:#ccf;\" | Date\n! style=\"background:#ccf;\" | Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''Major League Accomplishments & Awards'''\n|-\n| [[List of Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitchers|Chicago Cubs Opening Day starting pitcher]]\n| April 4, 2016\n| <ref name=2016OpeningDay />\n|-\n| [[Cy Young Award|National League Cy Young Award]]\n| 2015\n| <ref name=CyYoungESPN>{{cite web |last=Rogers |first=Jesse |title=Jake Arrieta wins NL Cy Young to continue Cubs' awards run |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/14165080/jake-arrieta-chicago-cubs-wins-national-league-cy-young-award |work=ESPN |date=November 18, 2015 |accessdate=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of Major League Baseball annual wins leaders|MLB Wins Leader]]\n| 2015\n| <ref name=CyYoungESPN />\n|-\n| Pitched a [[no-hitter]]\n| August 30, 2015; April 21, 2016\n| <ref name=AwardAugust2105 />\n|-\n| [[Major League Baseball Pitcher of the Month|National League Pitcher of the Month]]\n| 2015 (August & September); 2016 (April); 2017 (August)\n| <ref name=AwardAugust2105 /><ref name=AwardSeptember2015 />\n|-\n| [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week|National League Player of the Week]]\n| 2015 (July 6\u201312, August 24\u201330, & September 21\u201327)\n| <ref name=AwardLastWeekAugust2015 />\n|-\n| [[List of Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitchers|Baltimore Orioles Opening Day starting pitcher]]\n| April 5, 2012\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2015/04/06/every-baltimore-orioles-opening-day-starter-result/ |title=Every Baltimore Orioles Opening Day Starter & Result |publisher=CBS Baltimore |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''Minor League Accomplishments & Awards'''\n|-\n| [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] Pitcher of the Week\n| 2009 (May 18\u201324 & June 8\u201314)\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile>{{cite web |url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/player/453562/jake-arrieta |title=Jake Arrieta MLB Profile |publisher=MLB |date=2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[All-Star Futures Game]]\n| 2008\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/9085128/9085595 |title=Rosters for Futures Game 2008 official |publisher=CBS Sports |date=June 28, 2008 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Carolina League]] Pitcher of the Year\n| 2008\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| Carolina League Postseason All-Star\n| 2008\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| Carolina League Mid-Season All-Star\n| 2008\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/minors/carolina-league-takes-midseason-showdown/ |title=Carolina League Takes Midseason Showdown |publisher=Baseball America |author=Rode, Nathan |date=June 27, 2008 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Carolina League Pitcher of the Week\n| 2008 (May 12\u201318 & May 26 \u2013 June 1)\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| [[Arizona Fall League]] All-Prospect Team\n| 2007\n| <ref name=ArrietaMLBProfile />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" \"background:#ccf;\" colspan=\"3\" | '''College Baseball Accomplishments & Awards'''\n|-\n| [[Baseball America]] Second-Team All-American\n| 2006\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/college/awards/all-america-teams/2006/261703.html |title=2006 College All-America Team |publisher=Baseball America |date=June 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |