st2      = Miriam\n| authorlink2 = Miriam Lanskoy\n| last3       = Brzezinski\n| first3      = Zbigniew\n| authorlink3 = Zbigniew Brzezinski\n| title       = The Chechen Struggle: Independence Won and Lost\n| year        = 2010\n| publisher   = Palgrave Macmillan\n| isbn        = 978-0-230-10534-8\n}}\n\n* {{Citation\n| last1       = Soldatov\n| first1      = Andrei\n| authorlink1 = Andrei Soldatov\n| last2       = Borogan\n| first2      = Irina\n| authorlink2 = Irina Borogan\n| title       = The New Nobility: The Restoration of Russia's Security State and the Enduring Legacy of the KGB\n| year        = 2010\n| publisher   = PublicAffairs\n| isbn        = 978-1-58648-802-4\n}}\n\n* {{Citation\n| first      = John\n| last       = Dunlop\n| authorlink = John B. Dunlop\n| title      = The Moscow Bombings of September 1999: Examinations of Russian Terrorist Attacks at the Onset of Vladimir Putin's Rule\n| publisher  = Stuttgart: Ibidem\n| year       = 2012\n| isbn       = 978-3-8382-0388-1\n}}\n\n* {{Citation\n| first      = Brian Glyn\n| last       = WilliamsA\n| authorlink = Brian Glyn Williams\n| title      = Inferno in Chechnya: The Russian-Chechen Wars, the Al Qaeda Myth, and the Boston Marathon Bombings\n| publisher  = ForeEdge\n| year       = 2015\n| isbn       = 978-1-61168-737-8\n}}\n\n{{Chechen wars}}\n[[Category:Explosions in 1999]]\n[[Category:Russian apartment bombings| ]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Russia]]\n[[Category:Deep politics]]\n[[Category:Vladimir Putin]]\n[[Category:Building collapses in Russia]]\n[[Category:Chechen\u2013Russian conflict]]\n[[Category:Events in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Russia in 1999]]\n[[Category:Improvised explosive device bombings in Russia]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1999]]\n[[Category:20th-century mass murder in Russia]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1999]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Russia]]\n[[Category:1999 crimes in Russia]]\n[[Category:Murder in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Second Chechen War]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Moscow]]\n[[Category:1990s in Moscow]]\n[[Category:September 1999 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Document hippo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFOIA requests:period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_apartment_bombings"}
{"title_page": "Apollo in Real Time", "text_new": "'''Apollo in Real Time''' are interactive, multimedia websites that present the [[Apollo 11]], [[Apollo 13]], and [[Apollo 17]] missions as they happened at the time by compiling and synchronizing thousands of hours of audio and video recordings, transcripts, and photographs. Apollo historian Ben Feist created the Apollo 11 and Apollo 17 real-time sites, and then was hired by [[NASA]] to create the Apollo 13 real-time site. ''[[Air & Space/Smithsonian|Air & Space]]'' magazine describes the Apollo 13 site as \"one of the most ambitious multimedia history sites ever created\".<ref name=\"airspace\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airspacemag.com/daily-planet/relive-drama-apollo-13-real-time-it-happened-180974625/|title=Relive the Drama of Apollo 13 in Real Time, As It Happened|last=Reichhardt|first=Tony|website=Air & Space Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Website design==\n\nEach of the real-time sites is fronted by a dashboard that provides options for different audio and video channels. Viewers can explore the multimedia properties, search the transcript, or experience the in-progress feed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/escape-pandemic-dread-by-experiencing-the-apollo-13-mis-1842776645|title=Escape Pandemic Dread by Experiencing the Apollo 13 Mission in Real Time|website=Gizmodo|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Each media element is synchronized to the actual mission time's master clock, Ground Elapsed Time.<ref name=\"nasa\" /><ref name=\"fox\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/science/new-website-replays-apollo-11-first-moon-landing-mission-in-real-time|title=Apollo 11: New website replays first Moon landing mission in real time|date=2019-06-18|website=Space.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Apollo 17==\nThe Apollo 17 project, which Feist began in 2009 and launched six years later<ref name=\"nasa\" /> as a part-time hobby, was the first real-time site published. It includes raw audio from the onboard voice and air-to-ground communication channels in Mission Control that had been released by NASA, and film that had been collected by archivist Stephen Slater in the UK.<ref name=\"airspace\" />\n\n==Apollo 11==\n\nThe Apollo 11 real-time site covers the period from 20 hours prior to launch until just after recovery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigthink.com/technology-innovation/apollo-11-real-time|title=\u2018Apollo 11 in Real Time\u2019 website replays every second of historic mission|date=2019-07-16|website=Big Think|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and includes 11,000 hours of Mission Control audio, 2,000 photographs, and 240 hours of space to ground audio, as well as information on each of the lunar surface samples collected by [[Neil Armstrong]] and [[Buzz Aldrin]].<ref name=\"nasa\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/apollo-11-in-real-time-50-years-later|title=Apollo 11 in Real Time, 50 Years Later|last=Baldwin|first=Catherine|date=2019-07-12|website=NASA|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> For the Apollo 11 project, about 50 audio channel recordings were included,<ref name=\"airspace\" /> enabling viewers to select among every control position in Mission Control and other communication loops, such as the Guidance officer, the capsule communicator, and the flight dynamics officer.<ref name=\"fox\" />\n\nOn the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 mission, [[Space.com]] [[simulcast]] the live feed from the Apollo 11 in real-time site.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/relive-apollo-moon-landing-real-time.html|title=Relive the Apollo 11 Moon Landing Mission in Real Time!|last=July 2019|first=Tariq Malik 20|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Apollo 13==\n\n{{Quote box\n|quote=Being able to hear it now is really kind of cool, because you can start to understand how these flawed humans \u2014 like everybody else \u2014 were perfect in that moment, as they were working together to try to save the crew.\n|source=Ben Feist<ref name=\"verge\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 25em\n}}\nGathering historical materials for the real-time site for Apollo 13 took a team of researchers eight months.<ref name=\"verge\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21178364/apollo-13-in-real-time-website-50th-anniversary-history|title=This website lets you relive Apollo 13 in real time through historical transcripts, footage, and audio|last=Grush|first=Loren|date=2020-03-13|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Video footage for Apollo 13 includes both film from Mission Control and photos taken by the astronauts.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/11/us/apollo-13-anniversary-realtime-timeline-scn/index.html|title=Experience the Apollo 13 mission in real-time during its 50th anniversary|first=Ashley|last= Strickland|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The video and audio for the project were digitized and restored by a team of historians, researchers, and audio, film and visual experts.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> Apollo 13 in real-time includes four audio tapes from the time of the explosion that had been missing and were only recovered from the National Archives in fall of 2019. It is the first time this audio has been heard since the 1970 accident investigation.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> \n\nThe Apollo 13 site went live in April 2020 for the 50th anniversary of the launch.<ref name=\"airspace\" />  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://apolloinrealtime.org/11/ Apollo 11 in real-time]\n*[https://apolloinrealtime.org/13/ Apollo 13 in real-time]\n*[https://apollo17.org/ Apollo 17 in real-time]\n\n[[Category:Apollo 13]]\n[[Category:Apollo 11]]\n[[Category:Apollo 17]]\n[[Category:Apollo program missions]]\n", "text_old": "'''Apollo in Real Time''' are interactive, multimedia websites that present the [[Apollo 11]], [[Apollo 13]], and [[Apollo 17]] missions as they happened at the time by compiling and synchronizing thousands of hours of audio and video recordings, transcripts, and photographs. Apollo historian Ben Feist created the Apollo 11 and Apollo 17 real-time sites, and then was hired by [[NASA]] to create the Apollo 13 real-time site. ''[[Air & Space/Smithsonian|Air & Space]]'' magazine describes the Apollo 13 site as \"one of the most ambitious multimedia history sites ever created\".<ref name=\"airspace\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airspacemag.com/daily-planet/relive-drama-apollo-13-real-time-it-happened-180974625/|title=Relive the Drama of Apollo 13 in Real Time, As It Happened|last=Reichhardt|first=Tony|website=Air & Space Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Website design==\n\nEach of the real-time sites is fronted by a dashboard that provides options for different audio and video channels. Viewers can explore the multimedia properties, search the transcript, or experience the in-progress feed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/escape-pandemic-dread-by-experiencing-the-apollo-13-mis-1842776645|title=Escape Pandemic Dread by Experiencing the Apollo 13 Mission in Real Time|website=Gizmodo|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Each media element is synchronized to the actual mission time's master clock, Ground Elapsed Time.<ref name=\"nasa\" /><ref name=\"fox\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/science/new-website-replays-apollo-11-first-moon-landing-mission-in-real-time|title=Apollo 11: New website replays first Moon landing mission in real time|date=2019-06-18|website=Space.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Apollo 17==\nThe Apollo 17 project, which Feist began in 2009 and launched six years later<ref name=\"nasa\" /> as a part-time hobby, was the first real-time site published. It included raw audio from the onboard voice and air-to-ground communication channels in Mission Control that had been released by NASA, and film that had been collected by archivist Stephen Slater in the UK.<ref name=\"airspace\" />\n\n==Apollo 11==\n\nThe Apollo 11 real-time site covers the period from 20 hours prior to launch until just after recovery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigthink.com/technology-innovation/apollo-11-real-time|title=\u2018Apollo 11 in Real Time\u2019 website replays every second of historic mission|date=2019-07-16|website=Big Think|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and includes 11,000 hours of Mission Control audio, 2,000 photographs, and 240 hours of space to ground audio, as well as information on each of the lunar surface samples collected by [[Neil Armstrong]] and [[Buzz Aldrin]].<ref name=\"nasa\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/apollo-11-in-real-time-50-years-later|title=Apollo 11 in Real Time, 50 Years Later|last=Baldwin|first=Catherine|date=2019-07-12|website=NASA|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> For the Apollo 11 project, about 50 audio channel recordings were included,<ref name=\"airspace\" /> enabling viewers to select among every control position in Mission Control and other communication loops, such as the Guidance officer, the capsule communicator, and the flight dynamics officer.<ref name=\"fox\" />\n\nOn the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 mission, [[Space.com]] [[simulcast]] the live feed from the Apollo 11 in real-time site.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/relive-apollo-moon-landing-real-time.html|title=Relive the Apollo 11 Moon Landing Mission in Real Time!|last=July 2019|first=Tariq Malik 20|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Apollo 13==\n\n{{Quote box\n|quote=Being able to hear it now is really kind of cool, because you can start to understand how these flawed humans \u2014 like everybody else \u2014 were perfect in that moment, as they were working together to try to save the crew.\n|source=Ben Feist<ref name=\"verge\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 25em\n}}\nGathering historical materials for the real-time site for Apollo 13 took a team of researchers eight months.<ref name=\"verge\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21178364/apollo-13-in-real-time-website-50th-anniversary-history|title=This website lets you relive Apollo 13 in real time through historical transcripts, footage, and audio|last=Grush|first=Loren|date=2020-03-13|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Video footage for Apollo 13 includes both film from Mission Control and photos taken by the astronauts.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/11/us/apollo-13-anniversary-realtime-timeline-scn/index.html|title=Experience the Apollo 13 mission in real-time during its 50th anniversary|first=Ashley|last= Strickland|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The video and audio for the project were digitized and restored by a team of historians, researchers, and audio, film and visual experts.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> Apollo 13 in real-time includes four audio tapes from the time of the explosion that had been missing and were only recovered from the National Archives in fall of 2019. It is the first time this audio has been heard since the 1970 accident investigation.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> \n\nThe Apollo 13 site went live in April 2020 for the 50th anniversary of the launch.<ref name=\"airspace\" />  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://apolloinrealtime.org/11/ Apollo 11 in real-time]\n*[https://apolloinrealtime.org/13/ Apollo 13 in real-time]\n*[https://apollo17.org/ Apollo 17 in real-time]\n\n[[Category:Apollo 13]]\n[[Category:Apollo 11]]\n[[Category:Apollo 17]]\n[[Category:Apollo program missions]]\n", "name_user": "Schazjmd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApollo 17:tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollo_in_Real_Time"}
